    "finalTextLength": 2839,
    "finalText": "Start with what’s breaking down:\n\n**1. Weekly Work-Intake and Follow-Up**\nYou’re losing track of open items, owner assignments, and due dates. Fragmented follow-through is the biggest risk. You need a single, disciplined work intake and follow-up process. Every item—admin or client—goes into a common list, with today’s actions at the top and next week’s planned right below. Assign owners and deadlines for each. Separate urgent items (cash flow, compliance, client reversals) from general work.\n\n**2. Mail, Document, and Audit Workflow**\nProcessing is too ad hoc—mail, invoices, and tax documents stack up and get missed. Establish intake > scan > sort > escalate as a daily routine. There must be a regular check and overflow mechanism (i.e., Thursdays for regular processing, Fridays catch overflow), and everything time-sensitive gets flagged. Audit exposure and overlooked required docs are the cost of not owning this now.\n\n**3. Document Control for Projects**\nToo many versions, approvals, and milestones are floating without a single source of truth. Institute a project document control system—every milestone schedule, pay app, and major approval lives in a central spot, clearly named and version-controlled. Rework and confusion drop; project status is transparent at a glance.\n\n**4. Cross-Team Reporting Cadence**\nEvery function (ops, finance, BD, marketing) is reporting to someone—rarely at the same pace or with the same rigor. Set a recurring, organization-wide reporting rhythm. Use a unified template that shows progress, blockers, decisions needed, and next steps. Assign owners for collecting and distributing these updates.\n\n**5. Inbox Triage and Escalation**\nCritical emails/documents (finance, deadlines, customer-sensitive) must be triaged same-day. If something impacts cash flow, compliance, or a client deadline, escalate it inside 24 hours. Everything else hits the intake queue and gets worked according to standard schedule.\n\n**6. Operational Risk Register**\nTrack operational bottlenecks—backlog, audit issues, incomplete follow-ups, schedule drift—on a central risk register. Review it in weekly leadership meetings, not only in audits or fire drills.\n\n**Bottom line:**  \nActivity isn’t your problem—fragmentation and lack of follow-through are. These are process control issues, not effort issues. Systems fix this: centralize task tracking, enforce document flow, and run a real cadence on reporting and escalation.\n\n**First moves:**  \n- Today: Name a central place for intake/follow-up.  \n- This week: Assign owners for mail/document workflow and cross-team report collection.  \n- Next leadership meeting: Establish standing review of risk register and overdue actions.\n\nYou get more leverage fixing these touchpoints than chasing one-off problems. This is how you grow without spinning up more chaos.",
